he obstruction. arm so arm_joint_new ≤ arm_tgt. I can constrain darm directly by taking the minimum of the clipped value and the remaining distance to target, ensuring we never overshoot the goal position.\n\nRefining the move_action function... arm_raw extends by 0.046 in a single step, which is safe, so the real issue is overshooting the target. I need to modify the move_action function to clip the arm velocity so it never exceeds the target position—if the target is above the current position, cap the increase to the remaining distance, and if below, cap the decrease the same way. I'm realizing the bang-bang controller with clamping will stop exactly at the target without overshooting, which is cleaner than proportional control. For the x/y movement, the same approach works—clamping the error to the max speed means small errors get exact stops while large errors move at full speed until they shrink down. with error > DX_MAX, the robot moves at maximum speed, and when it gets close enough (within DX_MAX), it moves exactly to the target with no overshoot. So I'm switching to direct clipping for the movement actions instead of proportional gain. Since the robot can now stop precisely when the error is small enough, I'll set XY_TOL to 0.03 as a safety margin for floating point precision, and I need to determine the appropriate tolerance for arm movement as well.\n\nWith exact control, I can make ARM_TOL quite tight—something like 0.005 should work. Now let me update the code.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3680,"cache_read_input_tokens":118437,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3680},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4fa831d9-eb3f-4745-b971-234a10cba938","uuid":"fc1e7eee-f7f9-4429-9fe6-1c4964f87bc7"}
