bject's bottom and the floor.\n\nWorking through the math, if I pass the adjusted floor position to compute_arm_target, the arm target gets lowered by exactly PLACE_GAP, which means when the object is released it'll drop those 5mm to rest on the actual floor. Now I need to verify this doesn't break the existing behavior from the previous commit where the arm successfully reached 0.139042 without this gap adjustment. I'm checking whether the physics engine properly simulates free fall when objects are placed, since a small drop should be instantaneous anyway. Rather than adding a gap parameter to the placement logic, I could just increase the dump_pick_y height slightly—this keeps the arm target the same but raises the suction cup, which means the object releases higher above the floor and has room to settle naturally. CTION_OFFSET + PLACE_GAP`, then:\n- robot descends to dump_pick_y + PLACE_GAP (slightly higher)\n- arm_tgt = same (from pick formula, unchanged)\n- suction_y = (dump_pick_y + PLACE_GAP) - arm_tgt - SUCTION_OFFSET = suction_y_original + PLACE_GAP\n- obs_bottom = suction_y + PLACE_GAP - ob_h = dump_floor_y + PLACE_GAP\n\nWhen released: obs falls PLACE_GAP to dump_floor_y. ✓\n\nThis seems the simplest fix. Let me add PLACE_GAP=0.005 to dump_pick_y in ClearSurface.\n\nActually, I need to trace through why the formula changed between those two commits. In the earlier version, compute_safe_pick_y used TABLE_TOP_Y as a fixed reference point, giving an exact calculation. But in the later version, it switched to using the object's actual y position from the physics simulation, which introduces floating point drift—the object might be at 0.100000001 instead of exactly 0.1, and that tiny error propagates through the entire pick height calculation.\n\nWhen the object sits slightly below TABLE_TOP due to physics simulation precision, using its actual y position as the target makes the computed arm position place the object's bottom edge below the table, triggering 